==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sile
<hw>Sile</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Akin to Sw.
<ets>sila</ets> to strain, <ets>sil</ets> sieve, G. <ets>sielen</ets> to
draw away or lead off water. ⟦root⟧151<it>a.</it> See
<er>Silt</er>.]</ety> <def>To strain, as fresh milk.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sile</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sile
<hw>Sile</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To drop; to flow; to fall.</def>
<mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sile</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sile
<hw>Sile</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A sieve with fine
meshes.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Filth; sediment.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sile</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Sile
<hw>Sile</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Icel. <ets>s⟦imac⟧ld</ets> herring;
akin to Sw. <ets>sill</ets>, Dan. <ets>sild</ets>. Cf. <er>Sill</er> the
young of a herring.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A young or small
herring.</def> <mark>[Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Pennant.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

